Part A: Model Training and Evaluation

Q: 1. Choose a shallow (simple) classification baseline model from the ones mentioned in class after the midterm. A shallow classifier is one that doesn’t generate a complex decision boundary. We will use this classifier in the following points. Include a comment on why you choose this particular classifier and why is it considered shallow

Ans1: To make a simple starting point for classifying things, like sorting pictures into categories, I'd use Logistic Regression. It's like a basic tool that's easy to understand. Think of it as drawing a straight line to connect the features of the pictures (like colors or shapes) to figure out which category they belong to. It's not super fancy and can't handle really complex stuff, but it's good to get a basic idea. For our pictures, it works well because they have lots of features (784 pixels!) and need to be sorted into different groups.

Q2: Train the chosen baseline model on the training set. Make sure to use 5-fold cross-validation to properly judge the performance of the model on a validation set.

# Split the data into training and validation sets
x_train, x_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(x_train, y_train, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Flatten the target arrays
y_train, y_val = y_train.values.ravel(), y_val.values.ravel()

# Create and train the Logistic Regression model
model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=500).fit(x_train, y_train)

# Evaluate the accuracy on the validation set
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_val, model.predict(x_val))
print(f"Validation Accuracy: {accuracy * 100:.2f}%")

from sklearn.ensemble import BaggingClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

# Define the base model for bagging
base_classifier = LogisticRegression()

# Create BaggingClassifier with the base estimator
bagging_classifier = BaggingClassifier(base_estimator=base_classifier, n_estimators=10)

# Perform 5-fold cross-validation
cv_scores_bagging = cross_val_score(bagging_classifier, x_train, y_train, cv=5)

# Calculate the average accuracy across the folds
avg_accuracy_bagging = cv_scores_bagging.mean()

# Print the average cross-validation accuracy for bagging
print("Avg CV Accuracy (Bagging): {:.2f}%".format(avg_accuracy_bagging * 100))

from sklearn.ensemble import AdaBoostClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

# Define the base model for boosting
base_classifier = LogisticRegression()

# Create AdaBoostClassifier with the base estimator
boosting_classifier = AdaBoostClassifier(base_estimator=base_classifier, n_estimators=10)

# Perform 5-fold cross-validation
cv_scores_boosting = cross_val_score(boosting_classifier, x_train, y_train, cv=5)

# Calculate the average accuracy across the folds
avg_accuracy_boosting = cv_scores_boosting.mean()

# Print the average cross-validation accuracy for boosting
print("Avg CV Accuracy (Boosting): {:.2f}%".format(avg_accuracy_boosting * 100))

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.ensemble import BaggingClassifier, AdaBoostClassifier

# Load the trained baseline model (Logistic Regression)
baseline_model = LogisticRegression()
baseline_model.fit(x_train, y_train)
baseline_predictions = baseline_model.predict(x_test)
baseline_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, baseline_predictions)

# Load the trained bagging model with base estimator (Logistic Regression)
bagging_model = BaggingClassifier(base_estimator=baseline_model, n_estimators=10)
bagging_model.fit(x_train, y_train)
bagging_predictions = bagging_model.predict(x_test)
bagging_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, bagging_predictions)

# Load the trained boosting model with base estimator (Logistic Regression)
boosting_model = AdaBoostClassifier(base_estimator=baseline_model, n_estimators=10)
boosting_model.fit(x_train, y_train)
boosting_predictions = boosting_model.predict(x_test)
boosting_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, boosting_predictions)

# Compare the performance
print("Baseline Model Accuracy: {:.2f}%".format(baseline_accuracy * 100))
print("Bagging Model Accuracy: {:.2f}%".format(bagging_accuracy * 100))
print("Boosting Model Accuracy: {:.2f}%".format(boosting_accuracy * 100))

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.discriminant_analysis import LinearDiscriminantAnalysis as LDA

# Apply PCA
pca_model = PCA(n_components=2)
x_train_pca = pca_model.fit_transform(x_train)

# Apply LDA
lda_model = LDA(n_components=2)
x_train_lda = lda_model.fit_transform(x_train, y_train)

# Plot PCA and LDA
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

# Visualize PCA
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.scatter(x_train_pca[:, 0], x_train_pca[:, 1], c=y_train, cmap='viridis')
plt.title('PCA Visualization')
plt.xlabel('Component 1')
plt.ylabel('Component 2')
plt.colorbar()

# Visualize LDA
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.scatter(x_train_lda[:, 0], x_train_lda[:, 1], c=y_train, cmap='viridis')
plt.title('LDA Visualization')
plt.xlabel('LD 1')
plt.ylabel('LD 2')
plt.colorbar()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The PCA plot shows a smooth color transition, indicating a gradual change in the data. Colors overlap in the middle, suggesting some similarity between represented items. LDA Plot:

LDA plot has clearer separation between colors, utilizing label info for class separability. Still, there's overlap between adjacent classes, showing less distinct separation than PCA. Patterns:

PCA's spread indicates wide feature variation. LDA's tighter clusters suggest better class separability with label info. Overlap in both plots implies some common features between classes, typical for clothing items.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load datasets
import numpy as np
x_data = pd.read_csv('C:/Users/Andy/Desktop/ML/youseffs_lab/Fall2023/students-submissions/8920299/final_exam_part_b_dataset/tests/x_train.csv').astype('float32')
y_labels = pd.read_csv('C:/Users/Andy/Desktop/ML/youseffs_lab/Fall2023/students-submissions/8920299/final_exam_part_b_dataset/tests/y_train.csv').astype('int32')
#x_train = pd.read_csv('C:/Users/Andy/Desktop/ML/youseffs_lab/Fall2023/students-submissions/8920299/final_exam_part_b_dataset/tests/x_train.csv')
#y_train = pd.read_csv('C:/Users/Andy/Desktop/ML/youseffs_lab/Fall2023/students-submissions/8920299/final_exam_part_b_dataset/tests/y_train.csv')

# Apply PCA for 2D visualization
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
x_data_pca = pca.fit_transform(x_data)

# K-Means clustering with 5 clusters
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=5, random_state=42)
kmeansClusters = kmeans.fit_predict(x_data)

# Function to plot images for a specific cluster
def plot_images_for_cluster(cluster_index, num_images=10):
    cluster_indices = np.where(kmeansClusters == cluster_index)[0]
    
    if not cluster_indices.any():
        print(f"No data points in Cluster {cluster_index}. Skipping...")
        return
    
    random_indices = np.random.choice(cluster_indices, num_images, replace=False)
    
    # Plot each image in the subset
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, num_images, figsize=(12, 2))
    for ax, idx in zip(axes, random_indices):
        # Reshape the 784 features back into a 28x28 image
        image = x_data.iloc[idx].values.reshape(28, 28)
        ax.imshow(image, cmap='gray')
        ax.axis('off')
        ax.set_title(f'Label: {y_labels.iloc[idx].item()}')
    plt.show()

# Visualize random images from each cluster
for cluster_num in range(5):
    plot_images_for_cluster(cluster_index=cluster_num)

# Analyze clusters and suggest possible labels
print("\nAnalysis of Clusters:")
for cluster_num in range(5):
    cluster_indices = np.where(kmeansClusters == cluster_num)[0]
    if cluster_indices.any():
        cluster_labels = y_labels.iloc[cluster_indices].value_counts().idxmax()
        print(f"Cluster {cluster_num}: Possible Label - {cluster_labels}")
    else:
        print(f"Cluster {cluster_num}: No data points")
